# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geologist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner was born in Wehrau (now Osiecznica, Lower Silesian Voivodeship), a village in Prussian Silesia.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] His family had been involved in the mining industry for many years.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] His father, Abraham David Werner, was a foreman at a foundry in Wehrau.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner was educated at Freiberg and Leipzig, where he studied law and mining, and was then appointed as Inspector and Teacher of Mining and Mineralogy at the small, but influential, Freiberg Mining Academy in 1775.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] While in Leipzig, Werner became interested in the systematic identification and classification of minerals.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Within a year he published the first modern textbook on descriptive mineralogy, *Von den äusserlichen Kennzeichen der Fossilien* (On the External Characters of Fossils [or of Minerals]; 1774).
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] During his career, Werner published very little, but his fame as a teacher spread throughout Europe, attracting students, who became virtual disciples, and spread his interpretations throughout their homelands, e.g.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Robert Jameson who became professor at Edinburgh and Andrés Manuel del Río who discovered vanadium.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Socratic in his lecturing style, Werner developed an appreciation for the broader implications and interrelations of geology within his students, who provided an enthusiastic and attentive audience.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner's students Friedrich Mohs (who was in 1818 also successor to Werner's chair at the Freiberg Mining Academy), Robert Jameson and G.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Mitchell even had plans to establish an institute analogous to Freiberg Mining Academy in Dublin, which were due to the death of some people involved never carried out.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner was plagued by frail health his entire life, and passed a quiet existence in the immediate environs of Freiberg.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] An avid mineral collector in his youth, he abandoned field work altogether in his later life.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] There is no evidence that he had ever traveled beyond Saxony in his entire adult life.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] He died at Dresden from internal complications said to have been caused by his consternation over the misfortunes that had befallen Saxony during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] He is buried in the Neuen Annenfriedhof in south-west Dresden.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The grave is marked by a simple boulder inscribed with his name.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] He was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in 1810.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Starting from the pre-existing traditions of stratigraphy and cosmogony in Europe, Werner applied superposition in a classification similar to that of Johann Gottlob Lehmann.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Transition (*Übergangsgebirge*) Series: more indurated limestones, dikes, sills, and thick sequences of greywackes that were the first orderly deposits from the ocean.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] These were "universal" formations extending without interruption around the world.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Secondary or Stratified (*Flötz*) Series: the remaining, stratified fossiliferous rocks and certain associated "trap" rocks.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] These were thought to represent the emergence of mountains from beneath the ocean and were formed from the resulting products of erosion deposited on their flanks.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Alluvial or Tertiary (*Aufgeschwemmte*) Series: poorly consolidated sands, gravels, and clays formed by the withdrawal of the oceans from the continents.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Volcanic Series : younger lava flows demonstrably associated with volcanic vents.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner believed that these rocks reflected the local effects of burning coal beds.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The basic concept of Wernerian geology was the belief in an all encompassing ocean that gradually receded to its present location while precipitating or depositing almost all the rocks and minerals in the Earth's crust.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The emphasis on this initially universal ocean spawned the term "Neptunism" that became applied to the concept and it became virtually synonymous with Wernerian teaching, although Jean-Étienne Guettard in France actually originated the view.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] A universal ocean led directly to the idea of universal formations, which Werner believed could be recognized on the basis of lithology and superposition.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] He coined the term "geognosy" (meaning "knowledge of the Earth") to define a science based on the recognition of the order, position, and relation of the layers forming the Earth.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Moreover, he did not consider the Earth’s timescale to be compatible with the Biblical sources.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner believed that geognosy represented fact and not theory.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] His followers resisted speculation, and as a result Wernerian geognosy and Neptunism became dogma and ceased to contribute to further understanding of the history of the Earth.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] His former student Robert Jameson, who later became Regius Professor at the University of Edinburgh, founded the Wernerian Natural History Society in 1808 in honour of Werner.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] A principal focus of Neptunism that provoked almost immediate controversy involved the origin of basalt.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Basalts, particularly formed as sills, were differentiated from surface lava flows, and the two were not recognized as the same rock type by Werner and his students during this period.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Lavas and volcanoes of igneous origin were treated as very recent phenomena unrelated to the universal ocean that formed the layers of the Earth.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner believed that volcanoes only occurred in proximity to coal beds.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Burning melted overlying basalts and wackes, producing basalts and lavas typically at low elevations.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Basalt at higher elevations proved to Werner that they were chemical precipitates of the ocean.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] A second controversy surrounding Neptunism involved the volumetric problems associated with the universal ocean.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] How could he account for the covering of the entire Earth and then the shrinking of the ocean volume as the primitive and transitional mountains emerged and the secondary and tertiary deposits were formed?
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The movement of a significant volume of water into the Earth's interior had been proposed by the classical Greek geographer Strabo, but it was not embraced by Werner because it was associated with conjecture.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Nevertheless, with his views on basalt, he did not believe that the interior of the Earth was molten.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner appears to have dodged the question for the most part.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] He thought that some of the water could have been lost to space with the passing of some celestial body.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] That interpretation, however, raised the related question of explaining the return of the waters reflected in the secondary rocks.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner's ability as a lecturer attracted students from all over Europe.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Applications of his ideas fomented debate, particularly over the origin of basalt, in the so-called Neptunist-Plutonist controversy.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Among his most famous students was Alexander von Humboldt, who stayed in Freiberg in 1791-92, and initially subscribed to Werner's Neptunist ideas before departing from them in his later years.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The variety of scapolite known as wernerite is named in his honour.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner is credited with coining the term geognosy, for the geological study of the Earth's structure, specifically its exterior and interior construction.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] In 1805, he described the mineral zoisite and named it after Sigmund Zois, who sent him its specimens from Saualpe in Carinthia.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Werner’s major work, *Von den äußerlichen Kennzeichen der Foßilien* (1774), contained a comprehensive colour scheme he had devised for the description and classification of minerals.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The work, incorporating this colour nomenclature with some modifications, was translated into French by Claudine Guyton de Morveau (née Picardet) in 1790 and into English by Thomas Weaver in 1805.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] Patrick Syme (1774–1845), painter to the Wernerian and Horticultural Societies of Edinburgh, published in 1814 a revised version, entitled *Werner's Nomenclature of Colours, with Additions, arranged so as to render it useful to the Arts and Sciences*.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] In Germany, the scheme was favoured, for example, by the young polymath Novalis (Friedrich von Hardenberg) (1772–1801), who was impressed by its analytical character.
[src:geologist/abraham-gottlob-werner] The Werner Mountains in Antarctica and the Werner Range in Greenland were named after him.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The **Allegheny Mountain Range** (/ˌælɪˈɡeɪni/ *AL-ih-GAY-nee*)—also spelled **Alleghany** or **Allegany**, less formally the **Alleghenies**—is part of the vast Appalachian Mountain Range of the Eastern United States and Canada.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Historically, it represented a significant barrier to westward land travel and development.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies have a northeast–southwest orientation, running for about 300 miles (480 km) from north-central Pennsylvania southward, through western Maryland and eastern West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies comprise the rugged western-central portion of the Appalachians.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] They rise to 4,862 feet (1,482 m) in northeastern West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the east, they are dominated by a high, steep escarpment known as the Allegheny Front.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the west, they slope down into the closely associated Allegheny Plateau, which extends into Ohio and Kentucky.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The principal settlements of the Alleghenies are Altoona, State College, and Johnstown, Pennsylvania; and Cumberland, Maryland.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Using the United States Geological Survey (USGS) classification of physical geography (physiography), the Allegheny Mountain range is part of the Appalachian Plateau province of the Appalachian Highlands physiographic division.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The name is derived from the Allegheny River, which drains only a small portion of the Alleghenies in west-central Pennsylvania.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The meaning of the word, which comes from the Lenape (Delaware) Native Americans, is not definitively known but is usually translated as "fine river".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The suffix -ni means "of the", in Lenape, despite that geh is also Iroquoian for "of the".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] So, most likely, Alligehni or Oligini would be the Lenape name for the original homeland of the Erie people.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The word "Allegheny" was once commonly used to refer to the whole of what are now called the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] John Norton used it (spelled variously) around 1810 to refer to the mountains in Tennessee and Georgia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Around the same time, Washington Irving proposed renaming the United States either "Appalachia" or "Alleghania".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In 1861, Arnold Henry Guyot published the first systematic geologic study of the whole mountain range.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] His map labeled the range as the "Alleghanies", but his book was titled *On the Appalachian Mountain System*.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] As late as 1867, John Muir—in his book *A Thousand Mile Walk to the Gulf*—used the word "Alleghanies" in referring to the *southern* Appalachians.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] There was no general agreement about the "Appalachians" versus the "Alleghanies" until the late 19th century.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] From northeast to southwest, the Allegheny Mountains run about 300 miles (480 km).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] From west to east, at their widest, they are about 100 miles (160 km).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] When combining the Allegheny Province with the Kanawa Province, they run 400 miles (640 km).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The USGS physiographic classification of all land in the United States lists the Allegheny Mountains as a section within the larger Appalachian Plateau province.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It may be generally defined to the south by the Allegheny Front, and to the east by the Susquehanna River valley.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] To the west, the Alleghenies grade down into the dissected Allegheny Plateau.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The westernmost ridges are considered to be the Laurel Highlands and Chestnut Ridge in Pennsylvania, and Laurel Mountain and Rich Mountain in West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Big Stone Ridge marks the southern extent of the Alleghenies and is an outlier of Flat Top Mountain, with the Tug Fork river running along its western flank.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The land to the south and to the west of the Alleghenies is the Valley and Ridge physiographic province.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The eastern edge of the Alleghenies is marked by the Allegheny Front, which is also sometimes considered the eastern terminus of the Allegheny Plateau.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] This great escarpment roughly follows a portion of the Eastern Continental Divide in this area.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Several gorges and valleys drain the Alleghenies: to the east, Smoke Hole Canyon (South Branch Potomac River), and to the west the New River Gorge and the Blackwater and Cheat Canyons.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Thus, about half the precipitation falling on the Alleghenies makes its way west to the Mississippi and half goes east to Chesapeake Bay and the Atlantic seaboard.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The highest ridges of the Alleghenies are just west of the Front, with an east/west elevational change of up to 3,000 feet (910 m).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Absolute elevations of the Allegheny Highlands reach nearly 5,000 feet (1,500 m), with the highest elevations in the southern part of the range.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The highest point in the Allegheny Mountains is Spruce Knob (4,863 ft; 1,482 m), on Spruce Mountain in West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies contain relatively few large urban centers.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The four most populous cities in the region are, in descending order, Altoona, State College, and Johnstown in Pennsylvania, and Cumberland in Maryland.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the 1970s and 1980s, the Interstate Highway System was extended into the northern portion of the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The region is now served by a network of federal expressways—Interstates 80, 70/76 and 68.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Interstate 64 traverses the southern extremity of the range, but the Central Alleghenies (the "High Alleghenies" of eastern West Virginia) have posed challenges for highway planners owing to the region's rugged terrain and environmental sensitivities (see Corridor H).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The central Alleghenies continue to rely on a limited network of secondary highways, and the region maintains a lower population density compared to adjacent areas.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the telecommunications field, a unique impediment to development in the central Allegheny region is the United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), a large rectangle of land—about 13,000 square miles (34,000 km2)—that straddles the border area of Virginia and West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Created in 1958 by the Federal Communications Commission, the NRQZ restricts all omnidirectional and high-power radio transmissions, although cell phone service is allowed throughout much of the area.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Much of the Monongahela (West Virginia), George Washington (West Virginia, Virginia) and Jefferson (Virginia) National Forests lie within the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies also include a number of federally designated wilderness areas, such as the Dolly Sods Wilderness, Laurel Fork Wilderness, and Cranberry Wilderness in West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The mostly completed Allegheny Trail, a project of the West Virginia Scenic Trails Association since 1975, runs the length of the range within West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The northern terminus is at the Mason–Dixon line and the southern is at the West Virginia-Virginia border on Peters Mountain.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The bedrock of the Alleghenies is mostly sandstone and metamorphosed sandstone, quartzite, which is extremely resistant to weathering.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Prominent beds of resistant conglomerate can be found in some areas, such as the Dolly Sods.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] When it weathers, it leaves behind a pure white quartzite gravel.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The rock layers of the Alleghenies were formed during the Appalachian orogeny.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Because of intense freeze-thaw cycles in the higher Alleghenies, there is little native bedrock exposed in most areas.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The ground surface usually rests on a massive jumble of sandstone rocks, with air space between them, that are gradually moving down-slope.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The crest of the Allegheny Front is an exception, where high bluffs are often exposed.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Mineral springs in the High Alleghenies attracted Native Americans and 18th century white settlers and provided a modest incentive to the local economy.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The spas developing around these geological features include celebrated resorts that continue to cater to an exclusive clientele, such as The Greenbrier (White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia; hotel built 1858) and The Homestead (Hot Springs, Virginia; original lodge built 1766).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The High Alleghenies are noted for their forests of red spruce, balsam fir, and mountain ash, trees typically found much farther north.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Hardwood forests also include yellow birch (whose specific name *Betula alleghaniensis* refer to the mountain range), sugar and red maple, eastern hemlock, and black cherry.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] American beech, pine, oak, and hickory can also be found.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Chestnut trees used to be dominant throughout the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In some areas, it made up as much as 25 to 50 percent of the canopy, now they are found as stump sprouts as a result of blight.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The forests of the entire region are now almost all second- or third-growth forests, the original trees having been removed in the late 19th and (in West Virginia) early 20th centuries.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The wild onion known as the ramp (*Allium tricoccum*) is also present in the deeper forests.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Certain isolated areas in the High Alleghenies are well known for their open expanses of sphagnum bogs and heath shrubs (e.g., Dolly Sods, Cranberry Glades).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Many plant communities are indeed similar to those of sea-level eastern Canada.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] But the ecosystems within the Alleghenies are remarkably varied.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In recent decades, the many stages of ecologic succession throughout the area have made the region one of enduring interest to botanists.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The larger megafauna which once inhabited the High Alleghenies—elk, bison, mountain lion—were all exterminated during the 19th century.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] They survived longer in this area, however, than in other parts of the eastern United States.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Naturalist John James Audubon reported that by 1851 a few eastern elk (*Cervus canadensis canadiensis*) could still be found in the Alleghany Mountains but that by then they were virtually gone from the remainder of their range.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Mammals in the Allegheny region today include whitetail deer, chipmunk, raccoon, skunk, groundhog, opossum, weasel, field mouse, flying squirrel, cottontail rabbit, gray foxes, red foxes, gray squirrels, red squirrels and a cave bat.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Bobcat, snowshoe hare, wild boar and black bear and coyote are also found in the forests and parks of the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Mink and beaver are much less often seen.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These mountains and plateau have over 20 species of reptiles represented as lizard, skink, turtle and snake.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Some of the icterid birds visit the mountains as well as the hermit thrush and wood thrush.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] North American migrant birds live throughout the mountains during the warmer seasons.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Occasionally, osprey and eagles can be found nesting along the streams.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The hawks and owls are the most common birds of prey.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The water habitats of the Alleghenies hold 24 families of fish.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Amphibian species number about 21, among them hellbenders, lungless salamanders, and various toads and frogs.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies provide habitat for about 54 species of common invertebrate.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These include Gastropoda, slugs, leech, earthworms and grub worm.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Cave crayfish (*Cambarus nerterius*) live alongside a little over seven dozen cave invertebrates.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The indigenous people inhabiting the Allegheny Mountains emerged from the greater region's archaic and mound building cultures, particularly the Adena and Eastern Woodland peoples with a later Hopewellian influence.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These Late Middle Woodland culture people have been called the Montaine (c.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Their neighbors, the woodland Buck Garden culture, lived in the western valleys of the central Allegheny range.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Montaine sites extend from the tributaries of the upper Potomac River region south to the New River tributaries.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These also were influenced by the earlier Armstrong culture of the more southwestern portions northern sub-range of the Ouasioto (Cumberland) Mountains and by the more easterly Virginia Woodland people.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Late Woodland Montaine were less influenced by Hopewellian trade from Ohio, although similarly polished stone tools have been found among the Montaine sites in the Tygart Valley.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Small groups of Montaine people appear to have lingered much beyond their classically defined period in parts of the most mountainous valleys.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The watershed of the Monongahela River is within the northwestern Alleghenies, and it is from it that the Monongahela culture takes its name.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Godwin-Portman site (36AL39) located in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, had a possible Fort Ancient (c.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] AD 850 to 1680) presence during the 15th century.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Washington Boro ceramics have been found on the Barton (18AG3) and Llewellyn (18AG26) sites in Maryland on the northeastern slopes of the late Susquehannock sequence.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] AD 900 to 1630) are called the Drew Tradition in Pennsylvania.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] George: "I believe that some of the Monongahela were of Algonquin origin....
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Other scholars have suggested that Iroquoian speakers were interacting with Late Monongahela people, and additional evidence is presented to confirm this.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It is thought that these ancient Alleghenians were pushed from the classic Huffman Phase of the eastern slopes of the Alleghenies to the Blue Ridge Mountains in western Virginia, which was eastern Siouan territory.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In 1669, John Lederer and members of his party became the first Europeans to crest the Blue Ridge Mountains and the first to see the Shenandoah Valley and the Allegheny Mountains beyond.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The proto-historic Alleghenies can be exampled by the earliest journals of the colonists.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] According to Batts and Fallows' September, 1671 Expedition, they found Mehetan Indians of Mountain "Cherokee-Iroquois" mix on the New River tributaries.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] This journal does not identify the "Salt Village", but, that the "Mehetan" were associated with these and today thought to be "Monetons", Siouans.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] However, this journal does not identify the "Salt Village" below the Kanawha Falls, but, that simply the "Mehetan" were associated with these.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] He explained, below the "Salt Villages", a mass of hostile Indians had, implied, arrived and some believe these to be "Shanwans" of Vielles Expedition of 1692~94, ancient Shawnee.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In 1669, John Lederer of Maryland for the Virginia Colony and the Tennessee Cherokee had visited the mouth of the Kanawha and reported no hostilities on the lower streams of the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Mohetan representative through a Siouan translator explained to Mr Batts and Mr Fallon, Colonel Abraham Woods explorers 1671–72, that he (Moheton Native American) could not say much about the people below the "Salt Village" because they (Mountain Cherokee) were not associated with them.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Mohetan was armed by this time of 1671 for the Mohetan Representative was given several pouches of ammunition for his and the other's weapons as a token of friendship.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Somebody had already been trading within the central Alleghenies before the Virginians' historical record begins in the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Some earlier scholars found evidence these Proto-historics were either Cistercians of Spanish Ajacan Occuquan outpost on the Potomac River or Jesuits and their Kahnawake Praying Indians (Mohawk) on the Riviere de la Ronceverte.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The "Kanawha Madonna" may date from this period or earlier.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Where the New River breaks through Peters' Mountain—near Pearisburg, Virginia—the 1671 journal mentions the "Moketans had formerly lived".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] According to a number of early 17th century maps, the Messawomeake or "Mincquas" (Dutch) occupied the northern Allegheny Mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The "Shatteras" (an ancient Tutelo) occupied the Ouasioto Mountains and the earliest term Canaraguy (Kanawhans otherwise Canawest) on the 1671 French map occupied the southerly Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] They were associated with the Allegheny "Cherokee" and Eastern Siouan as trade-movers and canoe transporters.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Calicuas, an ancient most northern Cherokee, migrated or was pushed from the Central Ohio Valley onto the north eastern slopes of the Alleghenies of the ancient Messawomeake, Iroquois tradesmen to 1630s Kent Island, by 1710 maps.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Sometime before 1712, the Canawest ("Kanawhans"-"Canallaway"-"Canaragay") had moved to the upper Potomac and made a Treaty with the newly established trading post of Fort Conolloway which would become a part of western Maryland during the 1740s.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Prior to European exploration and settlement, trails through the Alleghenies had been transited for many generations by American Indian tribes such as the Iroquois, Shawnee, Delaware, Catawba and others, for purposes of trade, hunting and, especially, warfare.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Western Virginia "Cherokee" were reported at Cherokee Falls, today's Valley Falls of the Tygart Valley.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Indian trader Charles Poke's trading post dates from 1731 with the Calicuas of Cherokee Falls still in the region from the previous century.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The "London Scribes" (The Crown's taxation records) vaguely mentions the colonial Alleghenian location of only a few other early colonial trading locations.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] A general knowledge of these few outposts are more of traditional telling of some local people.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] However, an example is the "Van Metre" trading house mentioned in an earlier edition of the "Wonderful West Virginia Magazine" being on the South Branches of the upper reaches of the Potomac.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Another very early trading house appears on a lower Greenbrier Valley map during the earlier decades of the 18th century.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] As early as 1719, new arrivals from Europe began to cross the lower Susquehanna River and settle illegally in defiance of the Board of Property in Pennsylvania, on un-warranted land of the northeastern drainage rivers of the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Several Indian Nations requested the removal of "Maryland Intruders".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Some of these moved onward as territory opened up beyond the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The first permanent European settlers *west* of the Alleghenies have traditionally been considered to have been two New Englanders: Jacob Marlin and Stephen Sewell, who arrived in the Greenbrier Valley in 1749.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] They built a cabin together at what would become Marlinton, West Virginia, but after disputing over religion, Sewell moved into a nearby hollowed-out sycamore tree.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In 1751, surveyor John Lewis (father of Andrew Lewis) discovered the pair.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Sewell eventually settled on the eastern side of Sewell Mountain, near present-day Rainelle, West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] They may well have been the first to settle what was then called the "western waters"—*i.e.*, in the regions where streams flowed westward to the Gulf of Mexico rather than eastward to the Atlantic.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Among the first whites to penetrate into the Allegheny Mountains were surveyors attempting to settle a dispute over the extent of lands belonging to either Thomas Fairfax, 6th Lord Fairfax of Cameron or to the English Privy Council.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] An expedition of 1736 by John Savage established the location of the source of the North Branch Potomac River.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In March 1742, a frontiersman named John Howard—along with his son and others—had been commissioned by Governor Gooch to explore the southwest of Virginia as far as the Mississippi River.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Following Cedar Creek through the Natural Bridge, they floated in buffalo-skin boats down the New, Coal, Kanawha, and Ohio Rivers to the Mississippi.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Although captured by the French before he reached Natchez, Howard was eventually released and (in 1745) was interviewed by Fairfax.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Howard's description of the South Branch Potomac River resulted in the definite decision by Fairfax to secure his lands in the region.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] An expedition under Peter Jefferson and Thomas Lewis in the following year emplaced the "Fairfax Stone" at the source of the North Branch and established a line of demarcation (the "Fairfax Line") extending from the stone south-east to the headwaters of the Rappahannock River.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Lewis' journal of that expedition provides a valuable view of the Allegheny country before its settlement.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Jefferson and Joshua Fry's "Fry-Jefferson Map" of 1751 accurately depicted the Alleghenies for the first time.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the following decades, pioneer settlers arrived in the Alleghenies, especially during Colonial Virginia's Robert Dinwiddie era (1751–1758).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These included squatters by the Quit-rent Law.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Some had preceded the official surveyors using a "hack on the tree and field of corn" marking land ownership approved by the Virginia Colonial Governor who had to be replaced with Governor John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Royal Proclamation of 1763, issued by King George III of Great Britain, followed a few months after the Treaty of Paris (1763), which formally ended the Seven Years' War and transferred French territory in North America to Great Britain.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation set a geographical limit that (at least temporarily) forbade all new settlements west of a line drawn along the crest of the Appalachian Mountains, which was delineated as an Indian Reserve.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Extending from New England in the north to Georgia in the south, the Proclamation Line effectively bisected the Alleghenies by more or less following the Eastern Continental Divide through the region.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation Line was not intended to be a permanent boundary between the colonists and Native American lands but rather a temporary boundary that could be extended further west in an orderly, lawful manner.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It was also not designed as an uncrossable boundary; people could cross the line, but not settle past it.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Its contour was defined by the headwaters that formed the watershed along the crest of the mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] All land with rivers that flowed into the Atlantic was designated for the colonial entities.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In contrast, all the land with rivers that flowed into the Mississippi was reserved for the Native American populations.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation outlawed the private purchase of Native American land, which had often created problems.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Instead, all future land purchases were to be made by Crown officials "at some public Meeting or Assembly of the said Indians".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] British colonials were forbidden to settle on native lands, and colonial officials were forbidden to grant ground or lands without royal approval.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Organized land companies asked for land grants, but this was denied by King George III.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] British colonists and land speculators objected to the proclamation boundary since the British government had already assigned land grants to them.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Including the wealthy owners of the Ohio company, who protested the line to the governor of Virginia, as they had plans to settle the land to grow the business.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Indeed, many settlements already existed beyond the Proclamation Line, some of which were temporarily evacuated during Pontiac's War (1763-1766) and there were many already granted land claims yet to be settled.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] For example, George Washington and his Virginia soldiers had been granted lands past the boundary.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Prominent American colonials joined with the land speculators in Britain to lobby the government to move the line further west.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The colonists' demands were met and the boundary line was adjusted in a series of treaties with the Native Americans.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Even the temporary exclusion of settlers from this vast region created significant discontent between Britain and colonial land speculators and potential settlers.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Many colonists disregarded the Proclamation Line and its successors and settled in the west, creating more tension between them and the Native Americans.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation and access to western lands was one of the first major areas of dispute between Britain and the Thirteen Colonies and became a contributing factor leading to the American Revolution.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Trans-Allegheny travel had been facilitated when a military trail—Braddock Road—was blazed and opened by the Ohio Company in 1751.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] (It followed an earlier Indian and pioneer trail known as Nemacolin's Path.) Braddock Road connected Cumberland, Maryland (the upper limit of navigation on the Potomac River) and the forks of the Ohio River (the future Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It received its name from General Edward Braddock, the British commander of the North American phase of the Seven Years' War — known locally as the French and Indian War (1754–1763) — who led the ill-fated Braddock expedition four years later.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In addition to the war, hunting and trading with Indians were primary motivations for white movement across the mountains.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Permanent white settlement of the northern Alleghenies was facilitated by the explorations and stories of such noted Marylanders as the Indian fighter and trader Thomas Cresap (1702–1790) and the backwoodsman and hunter Meshach Browning (1781–1859).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] These immigrants were predominantly Scotch-Irish, German, and, to a lesser extent, British stock.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Braddock Road was superseded by the Cumberland Road—also called the National Road—one of the first major improved highways in the United States to be built by the federal government.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Construction began in 1811 at Cumberland and the road reached Wheeling, Virginia (now West Virginia) on the Ohio River in 1818.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Just to the south, the state-funded Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike was constructed to provide a direct route for the settlements of the Shenandoah Valley to the Ohio River by way of the Tygart Valley and Little Kanawha Rivers.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Planned and approved in 1826 and completed in 1848, the Staunton and Parkersburg was maintained by fees (tolls) collected at toll houses placed at regular intervals.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Construction on the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad began at Baltimore in 1828; the B&O traversed the Alleghenies, changing the economy and society of the Mountains forever.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The B&O had reached Martinsburg, (West) Virginia, by May 1842, Hancock, (West) Virginia, by June, Cumberland, Maryland, on November 5, 1842, Piedmont, (West) Virginia, on July 21, 1851, and Fairmont, (West) Virginia, on June 22, 1852.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Chesapeake and Ohio Canal—also begun in 1828, but at Georgetown—was also a public work of enormous economic and social significance for the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It approached Hancock, Maryland, by 1839.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] From the beginning, the B&O Railroad and the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal operated in bitter legal and commercial competition with one another as they vied for rights to the narrow strips of land along the Potomac.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] When the Canal finally reached Cumberland in 1850, the Railroad had already arrived eight years before.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Debt-ridden, the Canal company dropped its plan to continue construction of the next 180 miles (290 km) of the Canal into the Ohio Valley.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The company had long realized—especially with the difficult experience of digging the Paw Paw Tunnel—that the original plan of construction over the mountains and all the way down the Youghiogheny River to Pittsburgh was "wildly unrealistic".
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Public works financed at the state level were not lacking during this period.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Main Line of Public Works was a transportation network project built between 1826 and 1834 by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] It created a railroad and canal system across southern Pennsylvania between Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, intended to transport freight (notably including anthracite coal) and people with greater reliability, speed and capacity.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Main Line of Public Works included the Philadelphia and Columbia Railroad, the Allegheny Portage Railroad and the Pennsylvania Canal system.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Lying astride the border separating the Union and Confederacy, the Alleghenies were among the areas most directly affected by the American Civil War (1861–1865).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] One of the earliest campaigns of the War was fought for control of the Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike and for the access it provided to the B&O Railroad.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Battle of Rich Mountain (July 11, 1861) gave the Federals control of the turnpike, of Tygart's Valley, and of all of the territory of western Virginia to the north and west, including the railroad.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] (Union General George McClellan's victory in this theater would ultimately bring him promotion to commander the Army of the Potomac.) The Federals fortified at Cheat Summit, and the Confederates established strongholds at Camp Bartow and Camp Allegheny.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Here they faced each other warily through the fall of 1861 and the following winter.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Lee's attempt to attack Cheat Summit Fort (September 12–15, 1861) and Federal attempts to attack Bartow and Allegheny, all failed to change the strategic stalemate.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Finally, the harsh, high elevation winter achieved what the troops had failed to accomplish, and in the spring of 1862 both armies moved on down the pike to the Battle of McDowell (May 8, 1862), and then on to fight what became General Stonewall Jackson's Shenandoah Valley Campaign (spring 1862).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Two years later, much of this contested area (along with much else) became part of the new state of West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The very rugged terrain of the Alleghenies was not at all amenable to a large-scale maneuver war and so the actions that the area witnessed for the remainder of the conflict were generally guerrilla in nature.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] With the further spread of the railroad networks in the 1890s and early 1900s, many new towns developed and thrived in the Alleghenies.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The lumbering and coal industries that boomed in the wake of the railroads brought a measure of prosperity to the region, but most of the revenues flowed out of the mountains to the cities of the eastern seaboard where the captains of industry were headquartered.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] This inequity created a bitter legacy that would last for generations and form the foundation of the mountaineers' poverty and the area's immense environmental degradation.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The dam broke after several days of extremely heavy rainfall, unleashing 20 million tons of water (18 million cubic meters) from the reservoir known as Lake Conemaugh.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] (This body of water had been built as part of the Main Line of Public Works, then abandoned.) With a flow rate that temporarily equalled that of the Mississippi River, the flood killed 2,209 people and caused US$17 million of damage (about $425 million in 2012 dollars).
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The American Red Cross, led by Clara Barton and with 50 volunteers, undertook a major disaster relief effort.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Support for victims came from all over the United States and 18 foreign countries.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] After the flood, survivors suffered a series of legal defeats in their attempts to recover damages from the dam's owners.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Public indignation at that failure prompted the development in American law changing a fault-based regime to strict liability.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In the 1920s and '30s, Allegheny highways were extensively paved to provide access for automobiles.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The suffering occasioned by the Great Depression led to a major social experiment in 1933 aimed at providing opportunities for unemployed local miners and farmers.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] Construction of the settlement of Arthurdale, West Virginia was undertaken by the short-lived Subsistence Homesteads Division and with the personal involvement of First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt, who used her influence to win government approval for the scheme.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The aim was to encourage self-sufficiency and reduce dependence on both market forces and welfare provision.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The experiment failed through a clash of ideologies, between a strong emphasis on accommodating those most in need yet also having qualifications to ensure that the community would be self-governed in a professional manner.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The entrepreneurial community spirit never took hold, and the project is generally remembered as a classic failure, though some of its original residents continued to defend its principles.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] From the 1950s to 1992, the United States government maintained a top secret continuity program known as Project Greek Island at The Greenbrier hotel in the Alleghenies of southern West Virginia.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] In August 1963, at the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Dr.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The Flight 93 National Memorial is located at the site of the crash of United Airlines Flight 93—which was hijacked in the September 11 attacks—in Stonycreek Township, Pennsylvania, about 2 miles (3.2 km) north of Shanksville.
[src:geologist/allegheny-mountains] The memorial honors the passengers and crew of Flight 93, who stopped Al-Qaeda terrorists from reaching their intended target.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The **American Association of Petroleum Geologists** (**AAPG**) is one of the world's largest professional geological societies with about 17,000 members across 129 countries.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Over the years, the activities of the AAPG have broadened so that they bring together not just geology but also geophysics, geochemistry, engineering, and innovative analytics to enable the more efficient and environmentally-friendly approaches to the development of all earth-based energy sources.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] New transformative technologies, such as the ability to better characterize reservoirs through imaging and the integration of multiple data sources, are coupled with concerns about the environment.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Members and affiliated societies are very much involved in preserving the quality of groundwater, dealing responsibly with produced water, and understanding the mechanisms of induced seismicity.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In addition to subsurface investigations, the society supports mapping of the surface and the use of new technologies (UAVs, drones, big data analytics), with the goals of advancing the science and understanding of geological processes.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG publishes the *AAPG Explorer* magazine and *AAPG Bulletin* scientific journal, and co-publishes a scientific journal with the Society of Exploration Geophysicists called *Interpretation*.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization holds an annual meeting including a technical conference and exhibition, sponsors other conferences and continuing education for members around the world such as ongoing Geosciences Technology Workshops, and provides various other services to its members.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization also includes divisions focused on particular aspects of the profession.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] These include the Division of Environmental Geosciences, Division of Professional Affairs, and the Energy and Minerals Division.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The association membership has included Harrison "Jack" Schmitt, a U.S. astronaut who walked on the Moon.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] At its annual conventions and international conferences AAPG recognizes the distinguished contributions in the field of petroleum geosciences with various awards, including the Sidney Powers Memorial Award, Michel T.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Halbouty Outstanding Leadership Award, Grover E.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Murray Memorial Distinguished Educator Award, Wallace Pratt Memorial Award, and Ziad Rafiq Beydoun Memorial Award.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG IBA award is given immediately following the IBA competition that is held at that year's annual convention.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG promotes student involvement in the profession by holding an annual Imperial Barrel Award competition where geoscience graduate students are encouraged to explore a career in the energy industry.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In this global competition, university teams analyze a dataset (geology, geophysics, land, production infrastructure, and other relevant materials) and deliver their results in a 25-minute presentation.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The students' presentations are judged by industry experts, providing the students a real-world, career-development experience.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] IBA offers students and their faculty advisor a chance to win accolades for themselves and cash prizes for their schools, and winning teams travel free to the annual AAPG convention to network with both future colleagues and future employers.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The Correlation of Stratigraphic Units of North America (COSUNA) was a project of the AAPG which resulted in the publication of sixteen correlation charts depicting modern concepts of the stratigraphy of North America.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported the investigation of the earth, and over the years, ideas about how oil is formed have changed.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In the 1960s, the AAPG supported the then-revolutionary idea of plate tectonics (vs. isostasy), and looked at plate tectonics as a key to the evolution of basins, and thus the formation of oil and gas.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] An example is Tanya Atwater's work on plate tectonics.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] As a whole, women geoscientists have played an important role in the AAPG's 100-year history as scientists and leaders.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Since that time, the AAPG has worked closely with scientific organizations such as the USGS to apply new scientific breakthroughs to the generation, migration, and entrapment of oil and gas.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The results have brought new understanding of ultra-deepwater reservoirs (such as off the coast of Brazil).
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported geomechanics in order to be able to predict pore pressure and avoid drilling hazards.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has also been supportive of investigations having to do with the impact of policies of disposing of produced water by injecting it into deep formations.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Workshops and forums have been held since 2009 (Geosciences Technology Workshops) to analyze the problems and to discuss solutions.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] They have been held throughout the world, and are documented through the presentations.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The presentations from the workshops have been made available for free via the AAPG's open access online journal, Search and Discovery.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In 2006, the AAPG was criticized for selecting author Michael Crichton for their Journalism Award for *Jurassic Park* and "for his recent science-based thriller *State of Fear*", in which Crichton exposed his rejection of scientific evidence for anthropogenic global warming.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Schrag, a geochemist who directs the Harvard University Center for the Environment, called the award "a total embarrassment" that he said "reflects the politics of the oil industry and a lack of professionalism" on the association's part.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The criticism drew attention to the AAPG's 1999 position statement formally rejecting the likelihood of human influence on recent climate.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Acknowledging that the association's previous policy statement on Climate Change was "not supported by a significant number of our members and prospective members", AAPG's formal stance was reviewed and changed in July 2007.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The new statement formally accepts human activity as at least one contributor to carbon dioxide increase, but does not confirm its link to climate change, saying its members are "divided on the degree of influence that anthropogenic CO2 has" on climate.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG also withdrew its earlier criticism of other scientific organizations and research stating, "Certain climate simulation models predict that the warming trend will continue, as reported through NAS, AGU, AAAS, and AMS.
[src:geologist/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG respects these scientific opinions but wants to add that the current climate warming projections could fall within well-documented natural variations in past climate and observed temperature data.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The **American Geophysical Union** (**AGU**) is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization of Earth, atmospheric, ocean, hydrologic, space, and planetary scientists and enthusiasts that according to their website includes 130,000 people (not members).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU's activities are focused on the organization and dissemination of scientific information in the interdisciplinary and international fields within the Earth and space sciences.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The geophysical sciences involve four fundamental areas: atmospheric and ocean sciences; solid-Earth sciences; hydrologic sciences; and space sciences.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The organization's headquarters is located on Florida Avenue in Washington, D.C.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was established in December 1919 by the National Research Council (NRC) to represent the United States in the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics (IUGG), and its first chairman was William Bowie of the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey (USCGS).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] For more than 50 years, it operated as an unincorporated affiliate of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] On June 29, 1972, AGU was incorporated in the District of Columbia and membership was opened to scientists and students worldwide.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was intended to promote "pure" geophysics; exploration geophysics has its own society, the Society of Exploration Geophysicists.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In a March 1919 report by a committee chaired by Robert S.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Woodward of the Carnegie Institution, geophysics was defined as a collection of "borderlands" (closely related, mutually dependent subjects): astronomy, geodesy, geology, meteorology, oceanography, seismology, terrestrial magnetism, terrestrial electricity, tides, and volcanology.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was organized under seven sections: Geodesy, Seismology, Meteorology, Terrestrial magnetism and electricity, Oceanography, Volcanology, and Geophysical chemistry.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Hydrology was added in 1930 and Tectonophysics in 1940.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The first meeting of the AGU took place on April 23, 1920.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Up to 1930, the number of members was restricted and members were elected.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 1932 the first annual dues of US$2 were imposed.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The journal *Radio Science* is co-sponsored by the International Union of Radio Science.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The journal *Earth Interactions* is published in partnership with the American Meteorological Society (AMS) and the Association of American Geographers (AAG).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In addition, *International Journal of Geomagnetism and Aeronomy* is no longer published and AGU distributes *Chinese Journal of Geophysics* and *Nonlinear Processes in Geophysics*.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Many of the journals have high impact factors, with *Paleoceanography* having the highest within paleontology and *Reviews of Geophysics* the second highest within geochemistry and geophysics as of 2010.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU has also been publishing books for more than 85 years.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU co-published (along with the AMS and the AAG) its first electronic journal, *Earth Interactions*, in 1997.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] It started its own electronic journal, *Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems*, in December 1999.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] It made a full transition to electronic publishing in 2001.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] For all its journals, the electronic version became the publication of record.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] This was accompanied by a new identification scheme for articles that entirely did away with sequential page numbers.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Instead, each article had a digital object identifier (DOI).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] This new system was met with complaints from libraries and scientists.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The article numbers provided no clue for libraries to find an article in printed versions, and even scientific databases were not set up to handle DOIs.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU officials claimed that the problems were a temporary cost of being a frontrunner, but did retroactively assign each article a four-digit article number.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2012 the journals and books, including over one and a half million pages of legacy content, were transferred to the Wiley Online Library.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] John Wiley & Sons were recognized for this work with the IT Project Team of the Year Award at the UK IT Industry Awards for 2013.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Five AGU journals are open access only: *AGU Advances*, *Earth’s Future*, *Earth and Space Science*, *GeoHealth*, *JAMES*, and *Space Weather*.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The remainder are delayed open access journals, having free access after a two-year rolling period.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU hosts a number of blogs, collectively known as the AGU Blogosphere, informally publishing frequent updates on the Earth and space sciences.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU publications are copyrighted, but in the United States many exceptions to the exclusive rights of copyright are allowed under the fair use provision, part of the Copyright Act of 1976.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Making copies of publications are allowed for such uses as teaching and research as long as a set of four criteria are met.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] However, when Texaco's corporate library made systematic copies of journal articles for its collection, AGU and five other publishers took Texaco to court.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Texaco was fined and agreed to retroactively purchase a license from the Copyright Clearance Center.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] While more than 40 presidents have provided scientific leadership for the AGU since 1919, operational leadership has been provided by a larger team.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The first senior team member was John Adam Fleming, who was elected Secretary in 1925 and changed the name of his position to General Secretary.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] He served as a volunteer while working at the Department of Terrestrial Magnetism at the Carnegie Institution.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] By 1943, with the membership nearing 2,000, AGU recognized the need for a full-time professional administrator.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The post was renamed Executive Secretary and Waldo E.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] He served until 1970 and then Athelstan Spilhaus, Jr. was hired as executive director.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Medals have been named after Fleming and Smith.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU leadership in 2021 included, in addition to the president, a CEO, 4 executive vice presidents, 6 vice presidents, 7 directors, and a chief digital officer.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU offers several awards, medals and fellowships.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU nominates members for fellowship in the society.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU is divided into 25 sections that provide the main structure for managing volunteers, developing leaders and honoring scientists.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU holds an annual meeting every December (known as the Fall Meeting).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Until 2017, the meeting was held yearly in San Francisco.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Because of renovations at the San Francisco venue, the 2017 meeting took place in New Orleans and the 2018 meeting in Washington, DC.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] It returned to San Francisco in 2019 and its location will rotate among San Francisco, New Orleans, Chicago, and Washington, DC.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Previously, a second meeting was held every Spring (April through May) in locations around the world.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The latter grew out of AGU's annual Spring meeting, which had been held for many years in Baltimore, until declining interest caused AGU to move the meeting to different locations, starting with Boston in 1998.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] With the 2003 meeting in Nice, France, it became known as the Joint Assembly because AGU co-sponsors it with other societies such as the Geochemical Society, the Mineralogical Society of America (MSA), the Canadian Geophysical Union (CGU), and the European Geosciences Union (EGU).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The Fall Meeting had more than 25,000 attendees in 2018.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In addition to the Fall meeting that covers all areas of the geophysical sciences, AGU sponsors many specialized meetings that are intended to serve the needs of particular scientific disciplines or geographical areas, including the Ocean Sciences Meeting, which is held in even numbered years.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Small, highly focused meetings are offered through the Chapman Conferences.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The large numbers and international participation in the Fall Meeting results in a large contribution to greenhouse gases.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The 9500 participants in the 2002 meeting traveled an average of 8,000 kilometres (5,000 mi) to attend, producing 1.3 metric tons of carbon dioxide, or one-sixteenth of the average yearly emissions for Americans.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU has made some adjustments such as asking shuttle bus drivers to turn off their engines when they are not moving, but 95% of the emissions come from jet fuel.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In an unpublished study, David Scott and Lawrence Plug of Dalhousie University estimated that the AGU could reduce emissions by 7.7% if it moved the Fall Meeting to Denver, Colorado.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2017, the first joint JpGU-AGU meeting was held in Chiba, Japan.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The meeting was a joint effort between AGU and the Japan Geoscience Union.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] On occasion the AGU Council issues position statements on matters affecting public policy that are related to geophysics.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] These include biological evolution, natural hazards, science education and funding, and climate change.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU adopted its first position statement on climate change in December 1998.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The adopted position statement was backed up by a detailed supporting document.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU position statement has undergone several revisions, most recently revised and reaffirmed in 2012.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2014, AGU developed the Sharing Science program to provide scientists with the skills and tools that they need to communicate science with any audience.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The program offers resources, workshops, hands-on support, and opportunities to help scientists more effectively communicate with broader audiences about Earth and space science.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Audiences range from journalists, educators and students, policy makers, and the broader public.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Members of the AGU who work in politically controversial fields have come under legal attack.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] However, such legal challenges continue, so in 2012 AGU entered in a partnership with the Climate Science Legal Defense Fund to offer legal counseling at the Fall Meeting.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Gleick, a climate scientist and recipient of the MacArthur Fellowship, said he was motivated by frustration with the efforts of groups such as the Heartland Institute to attack climate science and scientists, but admitted that it was a serious lapse of judgement.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] He resigned from the task force on February 16, 2012, and was replaced by Linda Gundersen, director of the Office of Science Quality and Integrity at the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2017, AGU adopted and updated ethics policy, called the AGU Scientific Integrity and Professional Ethics.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Among other updates, the policy updated its definitions of what counts as scientific misconduct to include harassment, bullying, and discrimination.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Additionally, AGU staff are trained in how to address incidents of harassment at their annual meeting and wear "Safe AGU" buttons to signify themselves as resources.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] On February 27, 2018, AGU CEO Chris McEntee testified before the House Committee on Science, Space, & Technology Subcommittee on Research and Technology Hearing – A Review of Sexual Harassment and Misconduct in Science.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] His testimony was alongside those of Rhonda Davis, head of the National Science Foundation's (NSF) Office of Diversity and Inclusion, Kathryn Clancy, an anthropologist at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, and attorney Kristina Larsen.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In July 2019, the AGU was awarded a three-year grant from the Alfred P.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Sloan Foundation to launch the AGU Ethics and Equity Initiative, a collaboration among the AGU and the National Center for Professional and Research Ethics at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The initiative will tackle issues around sexual harassment and gender-based discrimination by developing new educational resources and tracking tools to measure impact.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In December 2022, AGU punished climate scientists Rose Abramoff and Peter Kalmus for misconduct, who interrupted a plenary session of the annual Fall Meeting with a call for scientists to engage in protest against climate change.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU removed their research presentations from the meeting, banned them from participation, launched a misconduct inquiry, and complained to Abramoff's employer, Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Kalmus and Abramoff further claimed that AGU threatened to have them arrested if they returned to the meeting.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Abramoff was fired by Oak Ridge in January 2023.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2014, the AGU accepted 5469 gifts, grants and pledges from individuals and corporations.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Of these, the 1919 Society (gifts of over $100,000) included ExxonMobil, Integrated Ocean Drilling Program Management International, and Nature's Own.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] AGU also was found to have many annual events sponsored by corporations, including an annual Student Breakfast (supported by ExxonMobil) and Amazon Web Services supported research grants and that offer access to its cloud computing resources.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In 2015, the AGU Board approved a new Organizational Support Policy.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The policy covers subjects such as advertorials and member surveys.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The sponsorship of AGU by ExxonMobil became a source of concern for many members after evidence surfaced that ExxonMobil had known about climate change for decades but had actively worked to undermine climate science.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] On February 22, 2016, a letter signed by 100 scientists was delivered to the AGU, requesting that they cut all ties with ExxonMobil and other companies that foster climate misinformation.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The AGU Board of Directors met on April 22, 2016, and voted to continue accepting sponsorship from ExxonMobil, arguing that there was not unequivocal evidence that ExxonMobil continues to participate in climate misinformation.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] Instead of making a short-term political statement, the Board wished to engage with the energy industry over the long term.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] In response, Senator Sheldon Whitehouse and Representative Ted Lieu sent a critical letter saying that ExxonMobil continues to fund climate denial and is misleading the AGU.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] The Union of Concerned Scientists also sent a letter urging them to reconsider.
[src:geologist/american-geophysical-union] However, in a meeting on September 23, 2016, the Board upheld its previous decision.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] The **American Geosciences Institute** (**AGI**) is a nonprofit federation of about 50 geoscientific and professional organizations that represents geologists, geophysicists, and other earth scientists.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] The organization's offices are in Alexandria, Virginia.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] The name of the organization was changed from the **American Geological Institute** on October 1, 2011.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] Since 1966, AGI has produced GeoRef, a literature database for those studying the earth sciences.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] AGI operates the Center for Geosciences and Society.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] AGI's monthly magazine *Geotimes* became *EARTH Magazine* on September 1, 2008, with an increased focus on public communication of geoscience research.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] In April 2019, *EARTH Magazine* suspended publication and was folded into *Nautilus Quarterly*.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] The stated mission of AGI is to "represent and serve the geoscience community by providing collaborative leadership and information to connect Earth, science, and people".
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] GeoRef offers a variety of specialized databases for researchers, educators, and students in specific areas of geoscience.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] AGI offers lessons and curricula designed for teachers of Earth sciences in schools (K-12).
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] These educational resources are created in partnership with geological organizations whose work is related to Earth science concepts.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] Every year in the second full week of October, AGI runs Earth Science Week, to promote understanding of Earth science and stewardship of the planet.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] The Geological Society of America (GSA) and the National Cooperative Geological Mapping Program of the U.S.
[src:geologist/american-geosciences-institute] Geological Survey hold the Annual Best Student Geologic Map Competition to bring together student geologic mappers from around the world.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:geologist/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The band members met in school and started recording together in various forms of collaboration from a young age.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 1999, they established the record label Paw Tracks, issuing what is now considered their debut album, *Spirit They're Gone, Spirit They've Vanished* (2000), as well as work by other artists.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The band's 2007 album *Strawberry Jam* was their first to chart on the *Billboard* 200.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Their 2009 follow-up *Merriweather Post Pavilion* was the band's most commercially successful album, reaching No.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] 13 on the US chart; its reverb-heavy psychedelic pop sound proved highly influential to independent music of the subsequent decade.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Records released under the Animal Collective moniker may include contributions from any or all of its members.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Evolving from early collaborations between Lennox and Portner, the collective was not officially established until all four members came together for the 2003 album currently titled *Ark*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Most prior collaborations between the band members were then retroactively classified under Animal Collective's discography.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the case of Dibb, who often takes breaks from recording and performing with the band, his time off does not constitute full leave.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective grew out of childhood friendships in Baltimore County.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Noah Lennox and Josh Dibb met in the second grade at the Waldorf School of Baltimore and became good friends.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After the eighth grade, Lennox went away to a Waldorf high school in Pennsylvania, while Dibb enrolled at The Park School of Baltimore, where David Portner had studied since grade school.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 1993, Brian Weitz moved from Philadelphia to Baltimore County and began attending Park as well, becoming friends with Portner.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] According to Lennox, they attended "progressive" schools that emphasized creativity, imagination and artistic self-expression as part of "a complete kind of education".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Weitz and Portner started playing music together at the age of fifteen because of their shared love of the band Pavement and horror movies.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Their musical range included cover songs by Pavement and The Cure as well as the songs "Poison" by Bell Biv DeVoe and "Seasons in the Sun" by Terry Jacks.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] When Portner and Weitz met Dibb later in high school, they started an indie rock band called Automine with schoolmates Brendan Fowler (a.k.a.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] BARR) and David Shpritz, being the only ones they knew who wrote their own songs.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] "We [once] set up a show with four bands—bands that were different formations of us", Portner remembered in an interview with *Baltimore City Paper*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] At that time, the group did not have any contact with the music scene in Baltimore and "was more about the back porch." In 1995, Automine self-released their first and only record, the 7-inch-single *Paddington Band*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Around that time, they also had their first experiences with psychedelic drugs like LSD and started to improvise while playing music.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The four started to discover psychedelic rock bands like Can and Silver Apples, as well as local experimental groups such as Climax Golden Twins and Noggin.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Meanwhile, Dibb had introduced Lennox to Portner and Weitz, and the four of them began playing music in different group lineups (and often solo), producing several home recordings and swapping them and sharing ideas.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Using a drum machine for the first time, Weitz and Portner started a duo named Wendy Darling, whose sound was inspired by soundtracks of horror movies like *The Texas Chain Saw Massacre* and *The Shining*, especially György Ligeti and Krzysztof Penderecki.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 1997, Lennox and Dibb both went off to college in the Boston area (Boston University and Brandeis University), and Portner and Weitz attended schools in New York City (NYU and Columbia University).
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Lennox and Dibb assembled Lennox's debut album, *Panda Bear*, during this time from the multitude of recordings Lennox had made in the previous years and established the label Soccer Star Records to release it.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Abhorring the new life as a student at NYU, Portner, along with Weitz, returned to Maryland every summer to meet Lennox and Dibb and play music together.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] At that time Portner was also working on a record, which eventually became *Spirit They're Gone, Spirit They've Vanished*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Portner asked Lennox to play drums on the record and they recorded them along with piano and acoustic guitars in the summer of 1999.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The rest of the year, Portner returned to Maryland on weekends to record overdubs and finish the mixing.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It was finally released in the following summer under the name *Avey Tare and Panda Bear*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Soccer Star morphed into the Animal label, with the intention of putting out music that came from the four musicians.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In parallel with his environmental policy and marine biology studies, Weitz hosted a noise show at WKCR, Columbia's college radio station.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On weekends, he and Portner borrowed avant-garde music records and listened to them all night at Weitz's dorm room which rapidly broadened their musical horizon.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the summer of 2000, the four friends spent several months at Portner's apartment in downtown New York City intensely playing music together using antiquated synthesizers, acoustic guitars, and household objects.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] According to Lennox, in this summer the basis for all of Animal Collective's later music was created.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] However, all recordings of this period were stolen when Portner changed apartments and packed up the car the night before he moved.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] While studying, Dave Portner organized shows at New York University for a while.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In class, he met and became friends with Eric Copeland, and Portner organized a show for Copeland's band Black Dice.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 2000, *Spirit They're Gone, Spirit They've Vanished* was finished, Lennox and Dibb left school in Boston and moved to New York, and the group's music became much more collaborative in nature.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After introducing Lennox to Copeland, Portner and Lennox played their first show together in New York at The Cooler with Dogg and Pony, The Rapture and Black Dice in late summer of 2000.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] This was also the first time they wore makeup and masks, which later became a prominent characteristic of the group's live performances.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] From there on, Portner wore a mask for the first two years of the group performing.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Lennox wore a panda hood on his head and later put face paint on; throughout the Europe tour in early 2004 he wore a white wig and went by the name Edgar.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Dibb performed masked during the *Here Comes the Indian* tour.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On the Australia tour in November 2006 and inspired by Halloween, they wore masks for the last time.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After Portner and Lennox had played clubs around New York in twos, Weitz came on board in the end of 2000 and began performing with them.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Much of the live material from this time eventually was on *Danse Manatee* (Catsup Plate), released by label owner and longtime collaborator Rob Carmichael, who has steered art direction for all Animal Collective releases since 2004.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] *Danse Manatee* was released in 2001 under the name of *Avey Tare, Panda Bear and Geologist*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The trio would also occasionally use the name *Forest Children* when performing live during this period.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Notably, the close friendship with Black Dice has been a major influence throughout the group's career.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the summer of 2001, Black Dice took them as support on their first tour, which was captured on the 2002 live album *Hollinndagain*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Ives, a boutique label run by Secretly Canadian which releases limited edition vinyl only records.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Limited to 300 copies, each of which featured a one-of-a-kind handmade cover, *Hollinndagain* is among the rarest of Animal Collective artifacts.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It was re-released, both on CD and vinyl, on October 31, 2006, through the Paw Tracks label.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] At this point, Dibb began to perform with the group.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The next album to be released was *Campfire Songs*, again working with Catsup Plate in 2003.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The *Campfire Songs* concept and some of the material dated back to the earliest Avey Tare and Panda Bear shows in New York.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Recorded live in 2001 on Portner's aunt's screened-in porch in Monkton, Maryland, the record is one take of five songs played straight through.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Attempting to make a record as warm and inviting as a campfire, the band recorded their performance straight to minidisc, with one recorder outside to grab the ambient sound of the environment.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Field recordings of the surrounding area were also added.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The original album is out of print but Paw Tracks reissued it on January 26, 2010.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After this recording session, they began to work on new material that was later released on *Here Comes the Indian.* It was at this time when they began to face serious problems within the group.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In early 2002, they went on their first big tour which took them to the South of the US.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Of this time, Portner said, "We all lost our minds on that tour".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Right before their next tour in summer, Weitz got the message that he was accepted to his first choice graduate school in Arizona.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After three chaotic days on the road with their tour van breaking down, equipment getting damaged, struggles with a lack of money, the tour was about to be cancelled.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On the Collected Animals message board, Weitz wrote, "At that point we all knew we'd get back from tour, record the songs, and then we needed space from each other, and we still had more than 2 weeks left on the road".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Worrying that *Avey Tare, Panda Bear, Deakin and Geologist* would be too long-winded a moniker, and with record companies advising that a unifying name would be necessary for the marketplace, the group decided to adopt a catch-all name.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Using their old label of Animal as inspiration, they picked "Animal Collective".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] This formation was intended to be different from a straightforward band, giving the musicians the freedom to work in combinations of two to four, as dictated by the project at hand or their mood.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Their first entry under this name was *Here Comes the Indian*, which was released in 2003 by their newly formed record label, Paw Tracks, formed with Carpark Records' Todd Hyman.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective makes decisions on what Paw Tracks is to release, while Hyman runs the day-to-day operations.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The Animal label was abandoned upon the formation of Paw Tracks.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] *Here Comes the Indian* was the first record to feature all four of Animal Collective.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After the two releases in 2003 attracted attention, Black Dice introduced the group to the Fat Cat Records label.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] After the dense soundscapes of *Here Comes the Indian*, Portner and Lennox decided to concentrate on more stripped-down material.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Each of them began composing material and they performed as a duo usually with just acoustic guitars, a single drum, some effects and their voices.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The duo toured the world for the better part of a year with this new material, opening for múm and Four Tet among others, before retreating to Lamar, Colorado to record the material with Rusty Santos, a New York musician and friend.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The result was the 2004 album *Sung Tongs*, released on Fat Cat Records, which received a favorable Pitchfork review.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the meantime, Brian Weitz returned from Arizona and he and Josh Dibb joined the duo again.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] All four started writing new songs together which finally ended up on their 2005 release *Feels*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective, as the duo of Panda Bear & Deakin (a.k.a.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Noah's Ark), toured in Japan for the first time in February 2004 with Carpark Records' artists Greg Davis & Ogurusu Norihide.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In early 2004, they started touring with their regular setlists including exclusively post-*Sung-Tongs* material, except for "We Tigers" and "Who Could Win a Rabbit?", which have been performed regularly up to the present.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] During their Europe tour, the group was introduced to Vashti Bunyan in Edinburgh, Scotland by Kieran Hebden (AKA Four Tet), who had recently played in Bunyan's band.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Being fans of the cult folk singer's 1970 album *Just Another Diamond Day*, the group had dinner with Bunyan and asked her to collaborate on some recordings.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The group encouraged her to sing lead vocals on three songs left over from the *Sung Tongs* era, released on the *Prospect Hummer* EP in early 2005.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Weitz, who had started a day job in early 2004, could not join this tour and therefore missed the recording session with Bunyan, but contributed one instrumental song to the EP.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Spring of 2005 saw the group refining soon to be released *Feels* material while on tour*.* The spring tour included performances at small to mid-sized venues such as BAR Nightclub in New Haven, Connecticut and the Bowery Ballroom in New York City.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Colleges and universities throughout the northeast United States also held concerts, including Middlebury College, Bennington College and State University of New York at Purchase.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Ariel Pink supported as an opening act for the tour and Animal Collective's sets were well received as the buzz around the band slowly increased.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In October 2005, Animal Collective released *Feels*, recorded in Seattle with Climax Golden Twins' Scott Colburn, known for his work with the Sun City Girls.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the summer of 2006, Dibb's father died, which led to a show breakup after only two songs at Rock Herk Festival on July 15.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In the late fall of 2006, Animal Collective released *People* in Australia as a 7" on their Australian label Spunk Records, and worldwide as a 12" and EP in early 2007 on FatCat Records.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It contains three studio songs "People", "Tikwid", and "My Favorite Colors", as well as a live version of "People".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In January 2007, Domino Recording Company announced that it would release the new, then still unnamed, Animal Collective album.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] During the recording process in early 2007, Dibb announced via the Collected Animals forum that he would take a break from touring for a "myriad of personal reasons" until fall.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective performed live as a three-piece from that time until late 2009 with Deakin making his return to live performances in 2011.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On July 4, 2007, *Strawberry Jam* was leaked online.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The album was released in the U.S. on September 11, 2007, and received much acclaim and multiple accolades, including Album of the Year from *Pitchfork Media* and *Tiny Mix Tapes*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The band toured extensively throughout 2007, completing several American and European tours.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Beginning in May 2007 the band debuted a brand new batch of post-*Strawberry Jam* live songs.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] These songs were written in an intense two-week session before the tour, months before the release of *Strawberry Jam*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On October 5, 2007, the band, in its full four-man line up (as opposed to its three-man lineup performances in 2007 and 2008) made their national television debut on Late Night with Conan O'Brien performing the song "#1" in support of *Strawberry Jam*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On March 12, 2008, *Water Curses* EP leaked and was released on May 5, 2008.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On April 9, the song "Water Curses" was released by itself digitally.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In early 2008, sans Dibb, the collective entered the studio to record tracks for their eighth studio album.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The album, entitled *Merriweather Post Pavilion* after the outdoor concert venue, officially was announced on the band's official website on October 5, 2008 and was released January 6, 2009.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It became the band's most commercially successful album, peaking at number 13 on the US *Billboard* 200 and selling over 200,000 copies.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The first single released from the album was "My Girls".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The band set to tour throughout Europe and US in 2009, notably being one of the headlining acts at September's ATP New York Festival, where Lennox also performed a solo set as Panda Bear.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Starting with their first tour dates in early 2009, the band introduced "What Would I Want?
[src:geologist/animal-collective] This song was also part of a BBC Session recording, and the May 2009 tour saw the debut of "Bleed" - both of these songs later were included on their *Fall Be Kind* EP.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On May 7, the band made their second television appearance, on the Late Show with David Letterman, performing the single "Summertime Clothes" from *Merriweather Post Pavilion*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The appearance included the regular three-man lineup indicative of their 2007–2009 tours, which excluded Josh Dibb.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Four dancers draped in sheets also appeared on-stage behind the band, a first in their live performances.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The video accompanied the release of the single on July 7, 2009, also featuring remixes by Zomby (Hyperdub), Dâm-Funk (Stones Throw), and L.D.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In an interview with Pitchfork Media, Portner announced the last single from the album would be "Brother Sport", released November 9 on vinyl with the live B-side "Bleeding".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The release of the *Fall Be Kind* EP followed on December 8, which included *Merriweather* leftovers "Graze" and "I Think I Can", along with "What Would I Want?
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Sky", containing the first legal Grateful Dead sample.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Also included were "On A Highway" and "Bleed".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] For four years, the band had been working on *Oddsac*, a visual record, with Danny Perez, who directed music videos for the band's "Who Could Win a Rabbit" and "Summertime Clothes" singles.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The movie featured visuals which were developed and edited simultaneously with the music they recorded for it.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Panda Bear stated they would like to "create a movie that would have visuals similar to what somebody would see if they closed their eyes while listening to Animal Collective's music".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Weitz further added that "it's the most experimental stuff we've ever done." According to Portner, "Maybe here and there, in our minds, there's some weird narratives going on.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The whole thing cohesively doesn't have one narrative; it's more of a visual or psychedelic thing.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The film premiered at the 2010 Sundance Film Festival on January 26.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] *Oddsac* was screened in theaters in North America and Europe in spring 2010, followed by a DVD release in August.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In January 2010, *LAS Magazine* posted an article about alternative music financing that points out Deakin's initiative to have fans pay for a trip to perform at Africa's Festival in the Desert.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Aside from touring New Zealand and Australia in December 2009, the band planned a break from their two years of touring to focus more on creating and writing music.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On November 13, Panda Bear announced a small European tour of his solo material in early 2010.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On March 4, 2010, Animal Collective collaborated once again with Danny Perez in the audio-visual performance piece *Transverse Temporal Gyrus* at the Solomon R.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Guggenheim Museum in New York City, celebrating its 50th anniversary.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Two years later, it was announced that a collage of studio and live recordings of music from the project would be released as a 12" vinyl LP on April 21 for Record Store Day 2012.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] During several interviews in the second half of 2010, Lennox and Portner mentioned plans for Animal Collective's next album, including writing all together in the same location and the possibility of recording the new songs before taking them on tour, neither of which had happened for a long time.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Portner revealed in October that the band would move back to Baltimore to write music there.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Near the end of October 2010, All Tomorrow's Parties announced that Animal Collective would be curating and headlining their UK festival in May 2011.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It was confirmed in late November 2010 that Deakin would be rejoining the group for this show as well as the rest of the shows of their new tour.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Before starting their first European tour of 2011, all four members of the band had a short tour of California leading up to an appearance at the Coachella Music Festival.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] At the shows, the band mostly played their newly written songs that were yet to be recorded.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On April 18 it was announced that Animal Collective would have a concert on July 9, 2011 at Merriweather Post Pavilion, the namesake of their eighth studio album.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] During this period, the members of Animal Collective were invited by Maryland Film Festival to share a favorite film with an audience.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On the evening of May 6, 2011, Avey Tare, Geologist, and Deakin presented a rare 35mm print of the 1983 Shaw Brothers production *The Boxer's Omen* in the historic Charles Theatre, and noted that another favorite film of the group was *House*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Portner, in an interview for Madison, revealed that they had just finished writing sessions and that they intended to start full recording sessions in January 2012 for the next album.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] "We just finished another two weeks of writing sessions and put together five new songs," he said, noting that the crew planned to begin full recording sessions in January.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] "We're really excited about this record...and it's been really fun jamming with those guys again." On May 6, 2012, they announced the release of a 7" through Domino Records, entitled "Honeycomb" / "Gotham".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Both tracks were immediately made available to stream through their website.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] One week later, Animal Collective released a video on their website indicating that the album *Centipede Hz* would be released in September 2012.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On September 1, 2015, the band announced a live album, titled *Live at 9:30*, released as a limited 3 disc LP and on digital platforms on September 4, 2015.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On July 15, 2015, EastWest Studios announced that the band had finished recording a new album in their Studio 3 room.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On November 25, the album was reportedly named *Painting With*, and debuted over the speakers of Baltimore/Washington International Airport, playing on loop until the evening.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Tare confirmed that "FloriDada", the impending single from the album, would be released on November 30.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The album was released in February 2016.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On November 16, the band released "Mountain Game", a song that was rejected for the *Red Dead Redemption* soundtrack.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On February 14, 2017, the band announced the release of *The Painters EP* later that week on the 17th.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It features two songs recorded during the *Painting With* sessions, as well as two songs recorded for the EP, "Kinda Bonkers" and a cover of Martha and the Vandellas' "Jimmy Mack".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On March 21, the band announced via their Instagram page their plans to release the *Meeting of the Waters* EP on Record Store Day 2017.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] It was recorded live in Brazil by Avey Tare and Geologist in 2016.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The process of recording this EP was featured on the first episode of "Earthworks" on Viceland.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On March 19, 2018, Animal Collective announced a tour where Portner and Lennox would play 2004's *Sung Tongs* in full.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] This was following a performance in 2017 for Pitchfork's 21st birthday where the duo also played the album live, and a two-night residency at the Music Box in New Orleans where Portner, Dibb, and Weitz played "site-specific music" with three accompanying musicians.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On July 16, 2018, the band announced the audiovisual album *Tangerine Reef*, which was released on August 17, 2018.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The group featuring all four members embarked on a short tour in late 2019 performing new material.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Production of a new album with all members participating began in early 2020 but was halted by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Work resumed later in the year, done remotely from the member's respective homes, with a goal of a 2021 release date.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 2020, *2 Nights*, a collection of archival live recordings from 2001 and 2002, was released on the band's Bandcamp page in June.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The records' profits were donated to Climate Justice Alliance and Deep South Center for Environmental Justice.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On July 2, the group announced a digital reissue of the majority of their back catalogue to Bandcamp, alongside the release of a new EP, *Bridge to Quiet*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Along with the reissue of their back catalogue, the band officially changed the cover of *People* to remove the 'mammy' and changed the name of *Here Comes the Indian* to *Ark*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective (specifically members Deakin and Geologist) contributed the soundtrack for Marnie Ellen Hertzler's debut film *Crestone*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On February 4, 2022, the group released *Time Skiffs* via Domino.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The announcement corresponded with the release of "Prester John", the album's lead single.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The band later released the singles "Walker" and "Strung with Everything", with the latter accompanied by a music video created by Abby Portner, band member Avey Tare's sister.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The final single to be released was "We Go Back".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On June 26, 2023, the group released the 22-minute song "Defeat", both digitally and as a 12-inch vinyl record, as the lead single from their next album.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] On July 24, the group announced the album would be titled *Isn't It Now?* and revealed its album art and track listing.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Like the previous album, *Isn't It Now?* was released by Domino on September 29.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Portner, Lennox, Weitz, and Dibb began as lo-fi indie rock musicians who, by high school, had amassed individual bodies of work recorded on cassette tapes.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Influenced by horror film soundtracks and 20th century classical music, along with a shared passion for vocal harmony the group progressed to "walls of drones with guitars and delay pedals and us screaming into mics," in Portner's words.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In college, Weitz and Portner listened to avant-garde records while Lennox explored electronic music, a style he took interest in after listening to The Orb's *UFOrb* (1992) in boarding school.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] When the group (sans Dibb) convened in 2000 after the recording of *Spirit They've Gone, Spirit They've Vanished*, they conducted improvisational music sessions which used vintage synthesizers, acoustic guitars and household objects.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 2005, Lennox spoke of it as a defining era: "everything since then has been a variation of what we explored that summer." The following album, *Danse Manatee* (2001), drew from freak folk, noise rock, ambient drone, and psychedelia.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Genres that have been used to label the band include experimental pop, psychedelic, electronic, experimental, indie rock, avant-pop, art rock, freak folk, noise pop, neo-psychedelia, and psychedelic pop.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Lennox compared Portner's songwriting to the songwriting of Fleetwood Mac's Lindsey Buckingham.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective are often compared to the American rock band the Beach Boys, a vocal group who performed original songs written by their co-founder and leader Brian Wilson, himself inspired by barbershop music and his use of psychedelic drugs.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] The comparisons led Thorin Klosowski of the publication *Westword* to negatively refer to Animal Collective's music as "two Beach Boys records [playing] at the same time".
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Animal Collective responded to the initial comparisons by recording "College", an "anti-Beach Boys" song from the album *Sung Tongs*.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] Lennox has expressed reverence for their album *Pet Sounds* (1966) and reluctance on being compared to the Beach Boys.
[src:geologist/animal-collective] In 2015, Animal Collective recorded their album *Painting With* in the same studio space once used by Wilson for the recording of *Pet Sounds* and *Smile*.
[src:geologist/geologist] A **geologist** is a scientist who studies the structure, composition, and history of Earth.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists incorporate techniques from physics, chemistry, biology, mathematics, and geography to perform research in the field and the laboratory.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists work in the energy and mining sectors to exploit natural resources.
[src:geologist/geologist] They monitor environmental hazards such as earthquakes, volcanoes, tsunamis and landslides.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists are also important contributors to climate change discussions.
[src:geologist/geologist] James Hutton is often viewed as the first modern geologist.
[src:geologist/geologist] In 1785 he showed a paper titled *Theory of the Earth* to the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:geologist/geologist] In his paper, he explained his theory that the Earth must be much older than had previously been supposed to allow enough time for mountains to be eroded and for sediments to form new rocks at the bottom of the sea, which in turn were raised up to become dry land.
[src:geologist/geologist] Hutton published a two-volume version of his ideas in 1795 (Vol.
[src:geologist/geologist] The first geological map of the United States was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:geologist/geologist] In 1807, Maclure commenced the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:geologist/geologist] Almost every state in the Union was traversed and mapped by him; the Allegheny Mountains being crossed and recrossed some 50 times.
[src:geologist/geologist] The results of his unaided labors were submitted to the American Philosophical Society in a memoir entitled *Observations on the Geology of the United States explanatory of a Geological Map*, and published in the *Society's Transactions*, together with the nation's first geological map.
[src:geologist/geologist] This antedates William Smith's geological map of England by six years, although it was constructed using a different classification of rocks.
[src:geologist/geologist] Sir Charles Lyell first published his famous book, *Principles of Geology*, in 1830.
[src:geologist/geologist] This book, which influenced the thought of Charles Darwin, successfully promoted the doctrine of uniformitarianism.
[src:geologist/geologist] This theory states that slow geological processes have occurred throughout the Earth's history and are still occurring today.
[src:geologist/geologist] In contrast, catastrophism is the theory that Earth's features formed in single, catastrophic events and remained unchanged thereafter.
[src:geologist/geologist] Though Hutton believed in uniformitarianism, the idea was not widely accepted at the time.
[src:geologist/geologist] Most geologists also need skills in GIS and other mapping techniques.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geology students often spend portions of the year, especially the summer though sometimes during a January term, living and working under field conditions with faculty members (often referred to as "field camp").
[src:geologist/geologist] Many non-geologists often take geology courses or have expertise in geology that they find valuable to their fields; this is common in the fields of geography, engineering, chemistry, urban planning, environmental studies, among others.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists, can be generally identified as a specialist in one or more of the various geoscience disciplines, such as a geophysicist or geochemist.
[src:geologist/geologist] Professional geologists may work in the mining industry or in the associated area of mineral exploration.
[src:geologist/geologist] They may also work in oil and gas industry.
[src:geologist/geologist] Some geologists also work for a wide range of government agencies, private firms, and non-profit and academic institutions.
[src:geologist/geologist] They are usually hired on a contract basis or hold permanent positions within private firms or official agencies (such as the Geological Survey and Mineral Exploration of Iran).
[src:geologist/geologist] Local, state, and national governments hire geologists to work on geological projects that are of interest to the public community.
[src:geologist/geologist] This 'wellbeing' is often in the form of greater tax revenues from new or extended mining projects or through better infrastructure and/or natural disaster planning.
[src:geologist/geologist] An engineering geologist is employed to investigate geologic hazards and geologic constraints for the planning, design and construction of public and private engineering projects, forensic and post-mortem studies, and environmental impact analysis.
[src:geologist/geologist] Exploration geologists use all aspects of geology and geophysics to locate and study natural resources.
[src:geologist/geologist] In many countries or U.S. states without specialized environmental remediation licensure programs, the environmental remediation field is often dominated by professional geologists, particularly hydrogeologists, with professional concentrations in this aspect of the field.
[src:geologist/geologist] Petroleum and mining companies use mudloggers, and large-scale land developers use the skills of geologists and engineering geologists to help them locate oil and minerals, adapt to local features such as karst topography or earthquake risk, and comply with environmental regulations.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists in academia usually hold an advanced degree in a specialized area within their geological discipline and are employed by universities.
[src:geologist/geologist] In Canada, National Instrument 43-101 requires reports containing estimates of mineral resources and reserves to be prepared by, or under the supervision of, a Qualified Person (QP) who has at least five years of experience with the reported minerals and is a member of a professional association.
[src:geologist/geologist] The QP accepts personal liability for the professional quality of the report and underlying work.
[src:geologist/geologist] The rules and guidelines codified in National Instrument 43-101 were introduced after a scandal in 1997 where Bre-X geologists salted drill core samples at a gold exploration property in Busang, Indonesia.
[src:geologist/geologist] The falsified drilling results misled Bre-X investors and upon discovery of the fraud, the company collapsed in the largest gold mining scam in history.
[src:geologist/geologist] In Europe exists the professional title of EurGeol (European Geologist) awarded by the European Federation of Geologists.
[src:geologist/geologist] Geologists may belong to a number of professional societies promoting research, networking, and professional development within the field.
